Count as of Friday 15 was 1,458,787. Data for Saturday is not available but we can use the data from Hopkins University which states 24,996 new case for Saturday. That leaves us with 1,500,000 - 1,458,787 - 24,996 = 16,217 new cases for Sunday to reach 1,500,000 cases. How likely are we to exceed 16,217 cases on Sunday? Last Sunday we had 17'605 but we are on downward trend. The week before we had 24'892 on average except sunday. This week we are at 23'895. I guess it's 50/50.

I misunderstood the time stamps in my previous forecasts. Two more days of reporting left. Need an average of 21k per day in order to break 1,500,000. Slightly fewer cases tend to be reported on Sundays and Mondays. Still think it's more likely than not that we reach 1,500,000, especially since testing capacity has improved.

1,458,787 as of 5/16. Would need a little more than 41,000 cases to break 1,500,000, but we haven't seen more than 30,000 in a day for weeks. Leaving 1% just in case of the low probability of a massive influx of tests or something.

As the number of confirmed cases picks up in the Midwest and some South states recently, I am trying to find a pattern in the testing strategy (in case there is one...). It appears to me that the increase in total new tests of the recent days have been assigned to half a dozen states which have not been tested very intensely (under-tested) before, as the Northeast states and D.C. plus CA have stood in the focus and absorbed most of the tests available. For the last four days it's been more confirmed cases, while the positivity rate has remained by and large unchanged. Maybe there is some kind of a correlation between the number or date of tests assigned to an individual state or county and its distance to D.C. ...Anyway those latest additional test may also have a larger range in testing time lag (average inherent time lag between the test being taken has been recorded and a negative or positive result has been recorded under the COVID Tracking project.), maybe even 12 to 96 hours, differing from state to state and maybe depending on its geographical "remoteness". All together this makes it harder to predict any effect of an increase in new tests today on the absolute numbers of increases in confirmed cases in the days ahead.
